## What is this project?

The **AWS Cloud Security Posture Monitor (CSPM)** is a fully serverless, automated security auditing system built on AWS. It continuously scans your AWS account across multiple services — IAM, S3, EC2, and CloudTrail — and checks every resource against the **CIS AWS Foundations Benchmark v1.5**, which is the industry-standard security checklist used by enterprises, banks, and government organisations worldwide.

When it finds a misconfiguration — a publicly accessible S3 bucket, a root account without MFA, an SSH port open to the internet — it immediately fires an alert to **Slack and email**, stores the finding in **DynamoDB** for historical tracking, publishes metrics to a live **CloudWatch dashboard**, and raises a **CloudWatch alarm** so your team knows within minutes, not months.

Everything — every AWS resource, every permission, every rule — is defined in **Terraform** and deployed with a single command. No clicking through the AWS console. No manual setup. No configuration drift.

---

## The Problem it Solves

Cloud misconfigurations are the number one cause of cloud data breaches. According to Gartner, through 2025, 99% of cloud security failures will be the customer's fault — not AWS's — and most of them will be misconfigurations that sat undetected for weeks or months.

The typical problems in any AWS account left unchecked:

- **Root account used for daily operations** with no MFA enabled — one stolen password and the entire account is compromised
- **S3 buckets with public access** — developers create buckets for testing and forget to lock them down
- **Security groups wide open** — port 22 (SSH) or 3389 (RDP) accessible from 0.0.0.0/0, exposing servers to the entire internet
- **Access keys never rotated** — an engineer leaves the company but their keys remain active for years
- **CloudTrail disabled or misconfigured** — no audit trail means breaches go undetected and forensics become impossible
- **No encryption by default** — EBS volumes and S3 objects stored in plaintext

These are not theoretical risks. They are the exact misconfigurations behind the Capital One breach (2019, misconfigured WAF), the Twitch leak (2021, misconfigured server), and hundreds of smaller incidents every month.

**This tool detects all of the above automatically, continuously, and without human intervention.**

