## AWS Services Used & Why

### ⚡ AWS Lambda

**What it is:** Serverless compute that runs code in response to events without provisioning or managing servers.

**Why we use it here:** The security scanner is event-driven — it needs to run on a schedule and in response to API events, not 24/7. Lambda is perfect because you pay only for actual execution time (typically 2–5 minutes per scan), and it scales automatically. There is no idle cost between scans.

**Why not EC2?** An EC2 instance running a scanner 24/7 would cost $8–$30/month just to sit idle between scans. It also requires OS patching, security hardening, and SSH access management — all of which are operational overhead that defeats the purpose of a security tool.

**Why not ECS/Fargate?** ECS is designed for long-running containerised workloads. Our scanner runs for 2–5 minutes once a day. Containers add startup overhead and complexity for a workload this simple and periodic.

**Configuration in this project:** Python 3.11 runtime, 256 MB memory, 300 second timeout, environment variables for SNS topic ARN, DynamoDB table name, and Slack webhook URL.

---

### 🕐 Amazon EventBridge

**What it is:** A serverless event bus that routes events between AWS services and triggers actions based on schedules or patterns.

**Why we use it here:** EventBridge serves two purposes in this project. First, it triggers the Lambda scanner on a daily cron schedule (`cron(0 6 * * ? *)` — 6 AM UTC every day). Second, it can be configured to trigger the scanner in real time when specific CloudTrail API events occur — for example, when someone creates a new S3 bucket or modifies a security group, the scanner runs immediately instead of waiting for the daily schedule.

**Why not CloudWatch Events?** CloudWatch Events is the older name for EventBridge. They are the same service now. EventBridge is the current, feature-rich version with support for third-party event sources and event buses. Always use EventBridge for new projects.

**Why not a Lambda cron trigger directly?** EventBridge rules are more flexible, observable, and easier to manage through IaC. You can pause, modify, or add multiple schedules without touching the Lambda function itself.

---

### 📦 Amazon DynamoDB

**What it is:** A fully managed, serverless NoSQL key-value and document database.

**Why we use it here:** Every finding from every scan is stored in DynamoDB with a unique ID, scan ID, timestamp, severity, resource ARN, description, and remediation steps. This gives us historical tracking — you can query "how many CRITICAL findings did we have last month vs this month?" and see your security posture improving over time. We also use DynamoDB's TTL (Time to Live) feature to automatically expire findings after 90 days, keeping the table lean without manual cleanup.

**Why not RDS (PostgreSQL/MySQL)?** RDS requires a VPC, subnets, security groups, and a persistent instance running 24/7. For a write-sometimes, read-rarely workload like storing security findings, that's massive overkill. RDS costs $15–$50/month minimum even when idle. DynamoDB on PAY_PER_REQUEST billing costs cents per month for this workload.

**Why not S3 + Athena only?** S3 + Athena is great for long-term audit logs and complex queries across months of data — and we do use it for that. But DynamoDB is better for the operational use case: "show me all CRITICAL findings from the last scan" because it supports fast key-based lookups without running a full Athena query every time.

**Schema design:** `finding_id` (partition key, UUID) + `timestamp` (sort key) allows efficient retrieval of all findings from a specific scan or time range.

---

### 📣 Amazon SNS (Simple Notification Service)

**What it is:** A fully managed pub/sub messaging service that can fan out messages to multiple subscribers simultaneously.

**Why we use it here:** SNS acts as the alerting backbone. When the Lambda scanner finds CRITICAL or HIGH severity issues, it publishes a single message to the SNS topic. SNS then fans that out to all subscribers — in our case, an email subscription and a Lambda that forwards to Slack. This decoupled design means we can add more notification channels (PagerDuty, Microsoft Teams, SMS) by simply adding a new SNS subscription without changing the scanner code at all.

**Why not SES (Simple Email Service) directly?** SES only does email. SNS can do email, SMS, HTTP webhooks, SQS queues, and Lambda — all from one publish call. If you ever want to add SMS alerts or pipe findings into a queue for another system, SNS supports it without architectural changes.

**Why not sending directly from Lambda to Slack?** We do also send directly to Slack via webhook for speed. But SNS handles the email subscription, confirmations, retry logic, and subscriber management. Doing all of that manually inside Lambda would be significant extra code with no benefit.

---

### 📊 Amazon CloudWatch

**What it is:** AWS's native monitoring and observability service for metrics, logs, dashboards, and alarms.

**Why we use it here — three distinct roles:**

**Logs:** Lambda automatically streams all `print()` output to CloudWatch Logs. Every scan's output, every check result, every error is captured and searchable. This is essential for debugging and audit trails.

**Custom Metrics:** After each scan, the Lambda publishes custom metrics to the `CSPM/SecurityFindings` namespace — `FindingsBySeverity` (broken down by CRITICAL/HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW) and `TotalFindings`. These metrics feed the dashboard and alarms.

**Dashboard + Alarms:** A CloudWatch dashboard visualises findings trends over time — you can see at a glance if your security posture is improving or degrading. A CloudWatch Alarm fires whenever `FindingsBySeverity[CRITICAL] > 0`, which triggers the SNS topic and sends an immediate alert.

**Why not Datadog or Grafana?** Both are excellent tools for production monitoring, but they require additional cost, accounts, and configuration. CloudWatch is native to AWS, zero-setup, and free for the metric volumes this project generates. For a portfolio project or internal tool, CloudWatch is the right choice. Datadog makes sense when you have multi-cloud or on-premise infrastructure to monitor alongside AWS.

---

### 🔍 AWS CloudTrail

**What it is:** A service that records every API call made in your AWS account — who did what, when, and from where.

**Why we use it here — two roles:**

**As a data source:** The scanner checks whether CloudTrail is correctly configured (multi-region enabled, log file validation on, KMS encryption). A misconfigured or disabled CloudTrail is itself a CRITICAL finding because it means you lose your audit trail — if there's a breach, you cannot do forensics.

**As a real-time trigger:** CloudTrail can send events to EventBridge in near-real-time. This means when someone creates a new S3 bucket, modifies a security group, or creates an IAM user, EventBridge sees the event and can immediately trigger the scanner. You catch misconfigurations within seconds of them being created, not 24 hours later.

**Why not just CloudWatch Logs for API activity?** CloudTrail is specifically designed for API auditing with structured, queryable records. CloudWatch Logs would capture Lambda output but not the full API call history across all AWS services. They serve different purposes and are complementary.

---

### 🔧 AWS Config

**What it is:** A service that records resource configuration changes and evaluates them against compliance rules.

**Why we use it here:** AWS Config maintains a configuration history of every resource in your account. When we enable it, we get a resource inventory and change timeline — if a security group was compliant yesterday but non-compliant today, Config captured exactly when and what changed. We forward Config findings into Security Hub for centralised aggregation.

**Why not rely on Lambda scans alone?** Lambda scans give you a snapshot at a point in time. Config gives you continuous change detection and a historical record. For compliance reporting, you need the history. Config and Lambda scanning are complementary — Config catches drift between scans; Lambda provides deeper, custom checks that Config rules cannot express.

---

### 🏢 AWS Security Hub

**What it is:** A centralised security findings aggregator that collects findings from AWS services (GuardDuty, Inspector, Config, Macie) and third-party tools into one dashboard.

**Why we use it here:** Security Hub provides a single pane of glass for all security findings across the account. We push our Lambda findings into Security Hub using the ASFF (Amazon Security Finding Format), which means they appear alongside findings from GuardDuty and Inspector. This is how enterprise security teams actually consume security data — not from individual service dashboards.

**Why not just use our CloudWatch dashboard?** CloudWatch shows our custom metrics. Security Hub aggregates structured findings with severity, resource details, and compliance status across all AWS security services. For a complete picture of account security, you want both.

---

### 🗄️ Amazon S3 (for audit logs)

**What it is:** Object storage for any type of data.

**Why we use it here:** CloudTrail delivers its full API log files to an S3 bucket. This provides long-term, tamper-evident storage of all API activity. We pair it with Athena (serverless SQL query engine) so you can run queries like `SELECT * FROM cloudtrail_logs WHERE eventName = 'DeleteBucket' AND eventTime > '2024-01-01'` against months or years of logs without any database to manage.

**Why not DynamoDB for logs?** DynamoDB is optimised for fast key-based lookups, not full-table scans across large datasets. S3 + Athena is the standard pattern for querying large volumes of structured log data cheaply.

