## Security Checks Implemented

### IAM Checks (CIS Section 1)

| Check ID | Title | Severity | Why it matters |
|---|---|---|---|
| CIS-1.5 | Root account MFA not enabled | CRITICAL | Root has unlimited power. No MFA = one leaked password = full account takeover |
| CIS-1.12 | Credentials unused for 90+ days | HIGH | Dormant credentials are a persistent attack surface. Attackers use them months after an employee leaves |
| CIS-1.14 | Access keys older than 90 days | MEDIUM | Old keys may have been exfiltrated without detection. Regular rotation limits the blast radius |
| CIS-1.8–1.11 | Weak password policy | MEDIUM | Weak passwords enable brute-force and credential-stuffing attacks |
| CIS-1.16 | Inline IAM policies on users | LOW | Inline policies are harder to audit and manage than group/role-based policies |

### S3 Checks (CIS Section 2)

| Check ID | Title | Severity | Why it matters |
|---|---|---|---|
| CIS-2.1.5 | Public access block not enabled | CRITICAL | Public S3 buckets are the most common cause of cloud data breaches |
| CIS-2.1.1 | No default encryption | HIGH | Plaintext data at rest is a compliance violation in most regulated industries |
| CIS-2.1.3 | Versioning disabled | MEDIUM | Without versioning, ransomware or accidental deletion permanently destroys data |
| CIS-2.1.2 | Access logging disabled | LOW | No logging = no audit trail for who accessed what data |

### EC2 / Security Group Checks (CIS Section 5)

| Check ID | Title | Severity | Why it matters |
|---|---|---|---|
| CIS-5.2 | SSH (port 22) open to 0.0.0.0/0 | CRITICAL | Exposes servers to brute-force attacks from the entire internet |
| CIS-5.2 | RDP (port 3389) open to 0.0.0.0/0 | CRITICAL | RDP is one of the most exploited protocols. Open RDP = active attack surface |
| CIS-5.2 | Database ports open to world | HIGH | Databases should never be directly internet-accessible |
| CIS-2.2.1 | EBS encryption by default off | HIGH | New volumes created by developers won't be encrypted unless this is set |
| CSPM-EC2-001 | IMDSv1 enabled (SSRF risk) | HIGH | IMDSv1 allows SSRF attacks to steal instance credentials via metadata endpoint |

### CloudTrail Checks (CIS Section 3)

| Check ID | Title | Severity | Why it matters |
|---|---|---|---|
| CIS-3.1 | No CloudTrail or not multi-region | CRITICAL | Without CloudTrail you have no audit trail. Breaches are invisible |
| CIS-3.2 | Log file validation disabled | MEDIUM | Without validation, an attacker with S3 access can delete or modify logs to cover their tracks |
| CIS-3.7 | Logs not KMS-encrypted | MEDIUM | Unencrypted logs can be read by anyone with S3 access to the bucket |

